Stocks in South Africa Snap Two-Day Gain; Barloworld, Coronation, PPC Move

-- B y   S i k o n a t h i   M a n t s h a n t s h a
-- 
2011-05-17T17:37:55Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-17/stocks-in-south-africa-snap-two-day-gain-barloworld-coronation-ppc-move.html
South Africa ’s FTSE/JSE  Africa  All
Share Index snapped two days of gains, declining 312.10, or 1
percent, to 31,843.91 at the 5 p.m. close in Johannesburg.  The following are among the most active stocks in the South
African market today.  African Dawn Capital Ltd. (ADW)  , the small-cap financial
services company, gained the most since February 2005, adding 4
cents, or 50 percent, to 12 cents, after saying it returned to
profit for the period through Feb. 28.  ArcelorMittal South Africa Ltd. (ACL)  , Africa’s largest
steelmaker, fell for the second day. The company and  Kumba Iron
Ore Ltd. (KIO) ’s Sishen Iron Co. Ltd. extended by a year an interim
supply agreement. The extension is allow for arbitration
proceedings that will take place in the first half of next year
to resolve a dispute over the price paid by ArcelorMittal South
Africa for its iron ore supplies. ArcelorMittal South Africa
dropped 1 percent to 79.91 rand while Kumba Iron Ore (KIO SJ)
decreased 0.6 percent to 438 rand.  Barloworld Ltd. (BAW)  , the world’s largest forklift
trader, climbed the most since April 6, jumping 2.29 rand, or
3.4 percent, to 69.29 rand. The company said it increased
revenue to 23.6 billion rand ($3.4 billion), from 20 billion
rand and more than doubled its dividend to 50 cents a share for
the six months through March from 20 cents a year earlier.  Ceramic Industries Ltd. (CRM)  , a tile and sink
manufacturer, jumped the most since Dec. 6, rising 5.06 rand, or
3.7 percent, to 143 rand. The company declared a special
dividend of 15 rand a share to return surplus cash to
shareholders, according to a regulatory statement today.  Coronation Fund Managers Ltd. (CML)  , a  money manager ,
advanced for the fourth day, rising 23 cents, or 1.2 percent, to
19.05 rand, the highest since June 17, 2003. Profit rose to
298.8 million rand in the first half through March compared with
224 million rand a year earlier, Coronation said in a statement
today.  Pretoria Portland Cement Co. (PPC SJ), South Africa’s
biggest cement producer, closed at the highest in five weeks,
gaining 45 cents, or 1.8 percent, to 25.75 rand. Chief Executive
Officer Paul Stuiver said he plans to announce projects outside
the country by the end of its financial year ending September.  Tiger Brands Ltd. (TBS)  , South Africa’s largest food
company, fell for a second day, losing 1.99 rand, or 1.1
percent, to 185 rand. The company said fiscal first-half
earnings a share fell as much as 3 percent.  To contact the reporter on this story:
